<paragraph blockId="40.[192,1440,1247,1656]" pageId="40" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,338,1247,1271]" pageId="40" pageNumber="39">Definition.</emphasis>
A sister genus to 
<taxonomicName authority="Evans, 1955" authorityName="Evans" authorityYear="1955" box="[568,811,1247,1271]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Stinga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="40" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[568,649,1247,1270]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="39">Stinga</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Evans" box="[659,811,1247,1271]" firstAuthor="Evans" pageId="40" pageNumber="39" pagination="54 - 88" refId="ref27591" refString="Evans, W. H. 1955. A catalogue of the American Hesperiidae indicating the classification and nomenclature adopted in the British Museum (Natural History). Part IV. Hesperiinae and Megathyminae. British Museum (Natural History); London. v + 499 p., pl. 54 - 88" type="book chapter" year="1955">Evans, 1955</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(
<typeStatus box="[829,883,1247,1271]" pageId="40" pageNumber="39">type</typeStatus>
species 
<taxonomicName authority="Edwards, 1878" authorityName="Edwards" authorityYear="1878" box="[988,1432,1247,1271]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Pamphila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="40" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="morrisoni">
<emphasis box="[988,1237,1247,1271]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="39">Pamphila morrisoni</emphasis>
Edwards, 1878
</taxonomicName>
) combined with 
<taxonomicName authority="Scudder, 1872" authorityName="Scudder" authorityYear="1872" box="[385,658,1279,1303]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Poanes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="40" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[385,471,1280,1303]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="39">Poanes</emphasis>
Scudder, 1872
</taxonomicName>
(
<typeStatus box="[677,731,1279,1303]" pageId="40" pageNumber="39">type</typeStatus>
species 
<taxonomicName authority="Scudder, 1863" authorityName="Scudder" authorityYear="1863" box="[838,1265,1279,1303]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Hesperia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="40" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="massasoit">
<emphasis box="[838,1077,1280,1303]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="39">Hesperia massasoit</emphasis>
Scudder, 1863
</taxonomicName>
) including its junior subjective synonym 
<taxonomicName authority="Scudder, 1872" authorityName="Scudder" authorityYear="1872" box="[513,834,1311,1335]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Phycanassa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="40" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[513,657,1311,1335]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="39">Phycanassa</emphasis>
Scudder, 1872
</taxonomicName>
(
<typeStatus box="[848,901,1311,1335]" pageId="40" pageNumber="39">type</typeStatus>
species 
<taxonomicName authority="Edwards, 1865" authorityName="Edwards" authorityYear="1865" box="[998,1370,1311,1335]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Hesperia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="40" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="viator">
<emphasis box="[998,1184,1312,1335]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="39">Hesperia viator</emphasis>
Edwards, 1865
</taxonomicName>
) (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 13" captionStartId="39.[192,275,1562,1584]" captionTargetBox="[192,1438,215,1528]" captionTargetId="figure@39.[192,1440,213,1528]" captionTargetPageId="39" captionText="Figure 13. Genomic trees of Hesperiina, Pericharini and relatives. See Fig. 2 legend for notations." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3677261" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3677261/files/figure.png" pageId="40" pageNumber="39">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
). Species of this genus were formerly placed in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Scudder" authorityYear="1872" box="[803,889,1344,1367]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Poanes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="40" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[803,889,1344,1367]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="39">Poanes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but are not monophyletic with it if 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Evans" authorityYear="1955" box="[1331,1412,1343,1366]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Stinga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="40" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1331,1412,1343,1366]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="39">Stinga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is considered a valid genus, because 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Evans" authorityYear="1955" box="[618,699,1375,1398]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Stinga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="40" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[618,699,1375,1398]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="39">Stinga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is sister to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Scudder" authorityYear="1872" box="[847,933,1376,1399]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Poanes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="40" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[847,933,1376,1399]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="39">Poanes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with exclusion of this genus. This genus constitutes the “ordinary terrestrial species” subgroup of Burns (
<bibRefCitation author="Burns" box="[980,1123,1408,1432]" firstAuthor="Burns" pageId="40" pageNumber="39" pagination="1 - 23" refId="ref26762" refString="Burns, J. M. 1992. Genitalic recasting of Poanes and Paratrytone (Hesperiidae). Journal of the Lepidopterists' Society 46 (1): 1 - 23." type="journal article" year="1992">Burns 1992</bibRefCitation>
) who gave and illustrated diagnostic genitalic characters for it, in contrast to “marsh dwellers” that are the true 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Scudder" authorityYear="1872" box="[1276,1362,1440,1463]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Poanes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="40" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1276,1362,1440,1463]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="39">Poanes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Most obvious diagnostic character is a very long (extending well beyond the body of aedeagus) and armed with spikes titillator in penis (in addition to two smaller ones), so prominent that it is even shown on Evans sketches (
<bibRefCitation author="Evans" box="[398,546,1536,1560]" firstAuthor="Evans" pageId="40" pageNumber="39" pagination="54 - 88" refId="ref27591" refString="Evans, W. H. 1955. A catalogue of the American Hesperiidae indicating the classification and nomenclature adopted in the British Museum (Natural History). Part IV. Hesperiinae and Megathyminae. British Museum (Natural History); London. v + 499 p., pl. 54 - 88" type="book chapter" year="1955">Evans 1955</bibRefCitation>
). Harpe upturned and touches ampulla, instead of being directed largely distad and leaving a gap between it at ampulla in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Scudder" authorityYear="1872" box="[802,888,1568,1591]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Poanes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="40" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[802,888,1568,1591]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="39">Poanes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In DNA, a combination of the following base pairs is diagnostic: aly525.55.2:G476C, aly378.21.7:A1612G, aly84.28.1:A602G, aly 
<date box="[1237,1362,1600,1624]" pageId="40" pageNumber="39" value="2631-04-13">2631.4.13</date>
:T68A, aly85.22.2:T1259C.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="40" pageNumber="39" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="40.[192,1440,1680,1737]" pageId="40" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,347,1680,1704]" pageId="40" pageNumber="39">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name is a masculine noun in the nominative singular, and is formed from the last syllable of the 
<typeStatus box="[370,423,1713,1737]" pageId="40" pageNumber="39">type</typeStatus>
species name.
</paragraph>
